@NODE "Introduction" "Introduction"

Using the handy little utility on aminet (dev/gui/Gui4Cli.lha) I whipped up a
small, basically functional GUI for the speakfreely programs.

The GUI will let you set hosts, ports, compression modes, debug mode and where
the sound is coming from and going to.  It also tries to implement a "press to
speak" mode of operation, so you're not chewing CPU cycles audio-compressing
empty packets while you aren't talking.  (You can leave it on send mode all the
time if you've got cycles to waste.)  This still requires a lot of support
programs, but hopefully once it's set up once, you won't need to play with all
the CLIs.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Requirements" "Requirements"

Requires:
    - comm/net/SpeakFreely.lha (obviously)
        (sfmike.direct and sfspeaker.direct should be in your path)

    - util/cli/Tbreak.lha  (for stopping the programs)

    - dev/gui/Gui4Cli.lha (for the simple GUI)

    - mus/play/Audio-Handler.lha (for the audio output.)

@ENDNODE

@NODE "How it works" "How it works"

    Make sure the following programs are in your path
        sfmike.direct, sfspeaker.direct, tbreak

    When you hit the 'press to speak' button, the GUI runs the 'sfmike.direct'
program in a background CLI with the options you have set.  When you hit the
button again (when it's now saying 'press to stop'), the GUI sends out a Tbreak
command, which breaks CLI commands.  'sfspeaker' runs in the same manner.

    This method has the obvious drawback that it wants to run 'sfmike' every time
you 'press to speak'.  Not really any way to get around this using this fudge
GUI, but you could put 'sfmike' in RAM: to make it start up more quickly.

    The GUI is set to some sensible defaults but it's easy enough to edit
'sf.gc' and change the presets.

        - default host is rpcp.mit.edu (an echo-server)
        - default sound input is 'pipe:a' this assumes that you are piping
            sound into 'pipe:a' using agmsrecord (see below)
        - default sound output is to 'aud:'

    *NOTE* Due to the fact that I don't have a sampler on my amiga I haven't
been able to test this GUI properly.  Sampler users might want to make a little
script which first calls "agmsrecord HZ 8000 pipe:a" and then calls the
GUI.  Please someone get back to me and tell me whether it works ok.  (Not sure
on whether it's safe to kill and re-open a pipe while agmsrecordsound is trying
to pipe stuff into the other end).

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Problems" "Problems"

    - any option changes you make in the gui won't take place until the next time
        you start the program to which the option applied.

    - the audio-handler buffers the sound. Often sound is left in the buffer
        and is unplayed until something comes into the buffer to force it out.

    - ugly. solution: write me a better one :)

    - the debug option probably only works if you start gui4cli from the CLI
        otherwise stdout goes to /dev/NULL

    - the gui is about the right dimensions on my 800x600 wb. Your mileage
        may vary.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Future" "Future"

    Improving on this GUI shouldn't be too difficult.  It's all in text for
Gui4Cli (which even has arexx capabilities). Don't be shy to send me any
improvements that you make yourself.

    - Include gadget to register on "look who's listening" servers

    - include checking of LWL servers to see who there is to talk to

    - Add file requestors to
        + sound input, so you can choose a specific file you want to send
        + sound output, so you choose a file to record to.

@ENDNODE

